segments.text: Mrs. Dona Coulter Carnes on March 24, 1975.
Ms. Dona is 96 years old and lives on the same property that her parents did, 502 East 26th in Bryan.
The town, when the people were beginning to find out that there was a new town opened up, they commenced to come to make themselves citizens.
And my father came as a young boy, a horseback from Nashville, Arkansas, to be one of the younger men
of our town.
And my mother came all the way from Nashville, Tennessee with her father and mother to Texas to find another home that they thought was nicer than where they came from.
And my father fell in love with my mother and they were married.
My mother was
raised by Dr. H.T.
Downard, and he was the first mayor of Bryan, Texas.
And he was one of the most active citizens that we had because when he came, there was no school.
And he sent all the way with his own money
to Louisville, Kentucky, from where his wife's people came from, and started a little neighbor school over what we call now Washington Avenue, and which is now used as a gas station.
But he paid for the schoolteacher and kept her in his home all that time.
was like most all the other little new towns, the merchants all bought their business houses around the courthouse.
You'll see that in traveling all over Texas and the new states, that that's the way they did.
It's over that way in Caldwell.
But whoever started that was doing it for
the almighty dollar and to get rich quick.
So the people who wanted to buy buildings and put up buildings didn't like that.
So that's the reason we have Main Street downtown Brian.
Now, you never have seen any of the stores until recently where one of them has been around the courthouse.
And my father
came here because his sister had married Colonel P.R.
Smith, who was one of the early merchants here in town, and built a store down on Main Street.
And then my father clicked for him, and P.R.
Smith was beginning to have a little trouble financially, and that
was hurting my father also because he had borrowed some of my father's money left from the estate, the Coulter estate in Arkansas.
So my mother says, now, don't you be discouraged if you don't get what $100, $50 is going in the bank.
And we are going to amount to something in this little town.
And whatever his salary was, she took half of that money
and put it in the bank.
And we, my father, after the first child was born, bought this piece of property here, the whole entire block of ground.
And he kept it that way because everybody had to look after a way to travel.
And my father had a horse.
and a buggy, and we had the finest milk cow that anybody could possibly buy.
And we had plenty of chickens and guineas and ducks and gardens and everything that it takes to make a happy home.
And we had a happy home.
I guess one of the most enjoyable, prosperous families that you could find anywhere.
And so my father soon had enough money saved up that he bought the dry goods store from his brother-in-law and a friend of his.
They were in together.
Mr. Bowers was the name.
Bowers and P.R.
Smith.
And my father bought.

their interest and so his business kept growing and growing and growing and my mother kept saving and saving and saving and finally they got enough money that they bought the building that the business was in which was a brick building.
All of Main Street was in deep sand, very deep sand.
And it was made extremely wide, much wider than any country town that you could see has.
And that was due to the ox teams that people would come.
They'd drive oxen to their farm wagons and come in, and they'd be parked right out on Main Street
We have a picture that shows that where all of the people are gathered.
And then finally, as time went by, a club was organized.
And from this club, they put just one standard of lights down Main Street for every block that they had.
They had two lights, one on
in the section of East Street.

And so it wasn't long until they began to, each merchant began to improve their buildings, and in all of the stores, they were all exactly alike, they had three openings, three doors, and to each entrance was two doors.
I made six doors for this whole entire store.
There was no show windows at all.
Absolutely nothing of that kind.
And every, every year store had these three exactly alike.
And finally, a man by the name of copy who had the hardware store put up a very lovely, fancy decorated building.
And one by one, various ones would add a little bit more to make his building just very attractive in every way.
We had no cement sidewalks.
No, the street, the sidewalks downtown was out of wooden plank.
And the women in those days wore long dresses.
down to their ankles.
You never saw a woman go in a shoe store and try on a pair of shoes.
She wouldn't dare to sit down in the chair and let a man try her shoes on her.
There's two things that she always took home to try on, and that was her shoes and her corset.
She never allowed
anybody to help.
In fact, there was no place to have it.
We had no dressing rooms for any of the stores at all in those days.
My father had a little show window that he got when he went to market one day, one year, and he took two men to lift it, and he'd put

women's hats in there maybe and show one week and next week he'd have his shoes and the next week he'd have something else in this one little show window but it had to be packed out by two of the clerks and put in the wall of one of the doors you know where the three doors all come together
We had no electric lights, all swinging lamps and wall lamps.

And of course, that was a thing that the clerks traded more than anything else to keep these lamps and the chimneys washed and keep them filled with kerosene oil to be ready for business the next day.
And we only had one school building.
And that was a very large building and a very pretty building, I thought.
And they added, finally added, when I was about eight years old, they added two sides that each side took care of two grades, one downstairs and one upstairs.
And there was only 10 grades.
And we thought we had mighty fine school teachers.
And the man in charge was Major Banks.
And he was a very fine, educated man.
And so we thought it was very fine.
And then, too, the churches were very good in the community.
The Methodist Church is where it is now.
and the ground was given to us by the H and T C railroad.
And then they took up a collection and built a wooden church there, which was always a joy to our family because we loved the church work.
My mother was a charter member of the church.
My father was not a,
Methodists at that time.
His family were Baptist people.
But he went on to the Methodist church and worked in the church Sunday school and the church proper as it came about.
They had things quite different then from what they do now.
The young people had what we called an Epworth League that we did our Christian work together.

in and it was very wonderful and and it brought us very close together too because everybody knew everybody else then in those days and they had a picket fence around the church where the people that couldn't walk and didn't have any way to get there they they just walked to church and uh our um

Horses and buggies didn't do very much good for that purpose, but there were some of the members who lived between here and college, and they had to come in their carriage, and their surrey, what they called a fringed top surrey, and they had a nice congregation, and everybody was very happy over there.

the situation of the church and we always had good pastors and were able to pay them a salary and they had, uh, uh, branch store, uh, uh, churches that they had to go to one, the preacher did, and he was paid mostly by farm products of chickens and, and fruits and vegetables and things of that kind.
And it was all very, very fine.
And then we had the courthouse was brought here from Madison, from the edge of town here.
And we took part in that.
I was thinking the other day to how I attended.
the service and the Masonic Lodge had charge of the laying of the cornerstone.

And so they built that lovely courthouse with the clock in it and the clock struck and everybody was happy and they could go by that because they could hear it all over town and also see it all over town.
And everybody went to church on time, went to school

on time and everywhere they went they were on on time and it's I don't know just exactly what year that they begin to spread out but of course I'm very glad to say that I have lived in the town long enough to see it progress from one thing to the other for

for the best of everybody concerned and now it's a very lovely little city and I'm glad I've had a part in it and my father and mother were very fine citizens and every house had a fence around it because the stock ran out and everybody's chickens ran out
And so if you didn't want it to happen to you, you just kept your gate closed, and that kept them out.
But it was a long time before we ever did get the fences down.
And it's so much nicer, of course, than to have the stock because it
It was just always hollering, oh, I wish so-and-so would come get that cow out of my yard.
And they did do a lot of damage to the flowers in the yard, and we had very little grass.
I can't remember ever having a lawnmower because everybody had just a regular dirt yard, and they had gardens where there was big enough
But on each block, there was always six or eight houses.
Sometimes it'd be four little houses on one half and four on the other or three on the other.
And that is a reason that we had this large place to hear, to live on, that we could enjoy.
being by ourselves and have our things so that they wouldn't bother other people and i i just don't know uh how much longer it's going to take to make us a real big city but
With A&M College booming like it is, and with the school spreading out, there was only one school when I was a child.
And when I came up and when I graduated, there was only one school.
And I went to Kidd Key College to finish my education, which was later terminated into the SMU.
So all of the Kid Key College students that were coming on that year got their diplomas from SMU after it started in Dallas.
And what else do you want to know?
Miss Dona, where did you meet your husband?
Oh, my husband.
Oh, sure.
I met him right here, honey.
He came over, and with two other men, they organized the Eagle.
And it was up over what we call now Worldwide Store.
But it was in a store, a grocery store, I believe it was, upstairs.
And so they stayed up there, and the other two moved.
One of them went to Huntsville because he thought Huntsville would make a bigger city than Brown did.
So he went over there and worked in the same paper that's still in existence over there, too.
And my husband's other partner then, he had to move on account of his little boy had developed consumption, and they had to move.
for his health, and that left all the double responsibility of running the paper and paying for it to my husband.
And then when I came back from Kedki College as a graduate and a young girl, he had met me just before I left to go to school where the LaSalle Hotel is now.
upstairs was a lovely place to have opera and hometown plays and graduation plays and whatever you want to use it for.
And it was a very lovely place to go to, too.
And so some of the boys gave three of the girls that were going off to college a big party.
And so that was his chance.
And he got one of the boys who knew me real well to make out my program and to put four dancers down for him.
And I thought I was very popular with the young man that took me, and I thought he was in love with me, or he wouldn't have taken so many dances with me.
But I found out afterwards that Mr. Collins had asked him to reserve some dances for him.
So he came up and was introduced to me.
And then ever after that, we were sweethearts.
So then he progressed along, and that was when the paper was just a weekly.
It was only printed once a week.
And then after that, he got out a daily.
It was a morning paper.
And he just, after we married, he had a beautiful bridal home

for me spread this office building is over there now and that office building is mine now they put up there which is very useful for the people lawyers who work close to the courthouse but anyhow i we stayed at home very little because he was afraid to leave me alone at night while he was working at the paper and
I stayed over here with my Papa and Mama.
And as I did for every other thing that I wanted, because I was raised the baby of the family.
And I've always been waited on.
But that's where he met me, was in this beautiful opera house.
I'd call it play house.

We especially had something to look forward to because every year there was an Indian show that came here and put on a show and that gave us children an idea to play with all during the year because we'd clean out the buggy house
And we'd all gather around and have an ending show.
And sometimes it would get so good that we thought the neighbors ought to come and they'd have to pay to come in.
So we charged for them to come to the show.
And we made our money that way, putting on ending shows, copying after the ones who came from
Town to town, I suppose they did, because we only had the one railroad at that time, and of course we didn't have the automobile.

And I have always said that I was never going to say I will not ride that, and I will not do that, because whenever I have ever done it, I have told a story, because I turned out to be one of the very first to do it.
And that is riding in an airplane.
I remember it so distinctly.
I remember two boys that had a little plane.
And they charged.
After I was left a widow, I began to travel over the years.
And I wrote the social column for the Eagle to help my husband.
And I kept that for 30 years, writing that social column every week.
It came out on Thursday.
And I wrote all my parties and weddings and what I thought would be of any interest in the social way.
to be put into this paper on Thursday.
So the paper then grew in interest and grew in interest.
And I got tired, and I stopped writing the paper.
But the paper progressed.
very nicely without my help.
I think it will continue to do so anyhow.
But everybody who owned any part in the paper sold recently, a few years back, to this company that owns it now.
How many brothers and sisters did you have?
I had two brothers and one sister.
Are they still living here?
No, all of the family is dead but me.
My doctor brother became, my two brothers went to A&M College and my sister graduated at Kidd Key College the same year that they graduated out there at 1895.
1805, I mean.
And, no, it was 1895.
So I was always the baby and the others always had to wait on me and and do my school work for me and everything like that, you know.
But my sister's son is living here and my doctor
My oldest brother finished at A&M with honors, and he won the first Ross Volunteer Medal that was ever presented at A&M College.
He was a cadet colonel out there, and he helped organize football.
He's famous.
It was organized in 1993, 1893.
That's the year that he went to A&M.
He and my brother Walter Colter went out there and stayed and had rooms.
And they didn't come home very often.
But the boys would come in so often, and I taught them how to dance.
They didn't know how to dance, and they'd come in on the 12 o'clock train, and my mother would feed them.
And then I'd dance with them until 3 o'clock in the afternoon and drive them down to the station.
And they'd get the train back to college.
And they only had two dances every year.
That was the Ross Volunteer and the commencement.
But they got out beautiful invitations.
And there were only 16 boys to graduate at that time.
They both were very, very popular students at A&M.
They were very likable businessmen when they got through.
Ms. Stone, I understand there were pretty bad floods and droughts here many years back.
Do you remember?
Well, at one time there was so many people died during the time because a terrible
Just a terrific cold spell wind came up with the hard rain at the same time that they were trying to save lives and save cattle down there.
While this terrible spell came, there were three or four that died from Brian that went down there.
Only I think there were five boys, as well as I remember, went down there together.
to try to help save cattle people.
And this terrible wind, and it was cold, bitter cold.
And they climbed into a tree to protect themselves.
And the wind was so strong, they took off their belts and tied themselves to the limbs of the tree.
And they were all killed, all froze to death.
except one to tell the tale.
And that was just one instance out of many, many, many.
Do you remember when that was?
No, I've forgotten what year it was.
But if I'd had time, I possibly would have been able to remember that.
But it was a long time ago.
And that was before the automobiles came in.
If I remember correctly, they had no automobiles.
These boys went down on the train in some way.
The INGN train had just been put in, and I think they went out on that.
And it went right through the richest part of it.
valley down there and it was an awfully sad thing but of course each family lost somebody some some farm worker or somebody who lived near them
